EXP1 

🔹 Basic Linux Commands (File & Directory)

Q1. What is Linux?
👉 Open-source operating system based on Unix operating system.

Q2. What is a command in Linux?
👉 Instruction given to OS through terminal.

Q3. What does pwd command do?
👉 Shows current directory path.

Q4. What is ls command?
👉 Lists files and directories.

Q5. What is cd command?
👉 Changes directory.

Q6. What is mkdir?
👉 Creates new directory.

Q7. What is rmdir?
👉 Deletes empty directory.

Q8. Difference between rm and rmdir?
👉 rm → deletes files/directories
👉 rmdir → deletes only empty directory

Q9. What is cp command?
👉 Copies files.

Q10. What is mv command?
👉 Moves or renames files.

🔹 File Management Commands

Q11. What is cat command?
👉 Displays file content.

Q12. What is touch command?
👉 Creates empty file.

Q13. What is chmod?
👉 Changes file permissions.

Q14. What is file permission in Linux?
👉 Controls read (r), write (w), execute (x).

Q15. What is head and tail?
👉 head → first lines
👉 tail → last lines

🔹 Process Management

Q16. What is a process?
👉 Program in execution.

Q17. What is ps command?
👉 Shows running processes.

Q18. What is top command?
👉 Displays real-time processes.

Q19. What is kill command?
👉 Terminates a process.

Q20. What is PID?
👉 Process ID (unique number).

🔹 System Calls (IMPORTANT)

Q21. What is a system call?
👉 Interface between user program and OS kernel.

Q22. Why system calls are needed?
👉 To access hardware safely via OS.

Q23. Types of system calls?
👉 File, Process, Device, Information

Q24. Example of file system calls?
👉 open(), read(), write(), close()

Q25. Example of process system calls?
👉 fork(), exec(), wait(), exit()


EXP3

🔹 Basic Concepts

Q1. What is CPU scheduling?
👉 Process of selecting which process gets CPU next.

Q2. What is a scheduling algorithm?
👉 Method used by OS to allocate CPU to processes.

Q3. Why is CPU scheduling needed?
👉 To improve CPU utilization and reduce waiting time.

🔹 Preemptive vs Non-Preemptive

Q4. What is non-preemptive scheduling?
👉 Once CPU is given, process runs till completion.

Q5. What is preemptive scheduling?
👉 CPU can be taken from a running process.

Q6. Example of non-preemptive algorithms?
👉 FCFS, SJF (non-preemptive)

Q7. Example of preemptive algorithms?
👉 Round Robin, SRTF (Shortest Remaining Time First)

Q8. Key difference between them?
👉 Preemptive = interrupt allowed
👉 Non-preemptive = no interruption

🔹 Important Algorithms

Q9. What is FCFS?
👉 First Come First Serve (simple queue based).

Q10. What is SJF?
👉 Shortest Job First (smallest burst time first).

Q11. What is Round Robin?
👉 Each process gets fixed time (time quantum).

Q12. What is SRTF?
👉 Preemptive version of SJF.

🔹 Time Calculations

Q13. What is burst time?
👉 Time required by process to execute.

Q14. What is waiting time?
👉 Time process waits in ready queue.

Q15. What is turnaround time?
👉 Completion time – arrival time.

Q16. What is response time?
👉 Time from request to first response.


