👇

🔹 Basic Concepts

Q1. What is process synchronization?
👉 Coordination of processes to share resources safely.

Q2. What is a critical section?
👉 Part of code where shared resource is accessed.

Q3. Why is synchronization needed?
👉 To avoid data inconsistency and race conditions.

Q4. What is a race condition?
👉 When output depends on execution order of processes.

🔹 Peterson’s Solution

Q5. What is Peterson’s solution?
👉 Software solution for mutual exclusion between 2 processes.

Q6. How many processes does Peterson’s algorithm support?
👉 Only 2 processes.

Q7. Which variables are used in Peterson’s solution?
👉 flag[2] and turn

Q8. What is the role of flag[]?
👉 Indicates interest of process to enter critical section.

Q9. What is the role of turn?
👉 Decides which process gets priority.


EXP5

🔹 Basic Concepts

Q1. What is a deadlock?
👉 Situation where processes wait forever for resources.

Q2. What are the necessary conditions for deadlock?
👉

Mutual Exclusion
Hold and Wait
No Preemption
Circular Wait

Q3. What is deadlock avoidance?
👉 Technique to prevent deadlock by checking safe state before allocation.

🔹 Banker’s Algorithm

Q4. What is Banker’s Algorithm?
👉 Deadlock avoidance algorithm that ensures system remains in safe state.

Q5. Why is it called Banker’s Algorithm?
👉 Works like a bank granting loans safely.

Q6. What is a safe state?
👉 System can allocate resources without deadlock.

Q7. What is an unsafe state?
👉 May lead to deadlock.

🔹 Data Structures Used

Q8. What are the matrices used?
👉

Allocation
Maximum
Need
Available

Q9. What is Need matrix?
👉 Need = Maximum – Allocation

Q10. What is Available?
👉 Free resources in system.


EXP6

🔹 Basic Concepts

Q1. What is memory management?
👉 Technique used by OS to manage main memory.

Q2. What is dynamic partitioning?
👉 Memory is divided into variable-size blocks based on process need.

Q3. Why dynamic partitioning is used?
👉 To utilize memory efficiently.

🔹 Fragmentation

Q4. What is fragmentation?
👉 Wastage of memory.

Q5. Which type occurs in dynamic partitioning?
👉 External fragmentation

Q6. What is external fragmentation?
👉 Free memory exists but scattered in small blocks.

🔹 Placement Algorithms
🔸 1. First Fit

Q7. What is First Fit?
👉 Allocates first block that is large enough.

Q8. Advantage of First Fit?
👉 Fast allocation.

Q9. Disadvantage?
👉 May create fragmentation.

🔸 2. Best Fit

Q10. What is Best Fit?
👉 Allocates smallest block that fits the process.

Q11. Advantage?
👉 Reduces memory wastage.

Q12. Disadvantage?
👉 Slower (searches entire memory).

🔸 3. Worst Fit

Q13. What is Worst Fit?
👉 Allocates largest available block.

Q14. Advantage?
👉 Leaves large free blocks.

Q15. Disadvantage?
👉 Inefficient memory use.

🔹 Programming Related

Q21. What input is required?
👉 Memory block sizes and process sizes.

Q22. What output is expected?
👉 Allocation result (which process → which block).

Q23. Which language is used?
👉 C / C++

🔹 Advanced Viva Questions

Q24. What is compaction?
👉 Rearranging memory to remove fragmentation.

Q25. Limitation of dynamic partitioning?
👉 External fragmentation.

Q26. Static vs Dynamic partitioning?
👉 Static = fixed size
👉 Dynamic = variable size

EXP7

🔹 Basic Concepts

Q1. What is virtual memory?
👉 Technique that uses disk as an extension of RAM.

Q2. What is a page?
👉 Fixed-size block of memory.

Q3. What is paging?
👉 Dividing memory into pages and frames.

🔹 Page Fault

Q4. What is a page fault?
👉 Occurs when required page is not in main memory.

Q5. What happens during a page fault?
👉 OS loads page from disk into memory.

🔹 Page Replacement

Q6. What is page replacement?
👉 Replacing an existing page to load a new page.

Q7. Why page replacement is needed?
👉 Because memory is limited.

🔹 Page Replacement Algorithms
🔸 FIFO (First In First Out)

Q8. What is FIFO?
👉 Oldest page is removed first.

Q9. Advantage?
👉 Simple to implement.

Q10. Disadvantage?
👉 May remove important pages.

🔸 LRU (Least Recently Used)

Q11. What is LRU?
👉 Removes page not used for longest time.

Q12. Advantage?
👉 Better performance than FIFO.

Q13. Disadvantage?
👉 Complex to implement.

🔸 Optimal

Q14. What is Optimal algorithm?
👉 Removes page that will not be used in future.

Q15. Advantage?
👉 Minimum page faults.

Q16. Disadvantage?
👉 Not practical (future knowledge needed).

🔹 Advanced Questions

Q21. What is thrashing?
👉 Too many page faults → system slows down.

Q22. What is Belady’s anomaly?
👉 Increasing frames increases page faults (in FIFO).

Q23. Which algorithm avoids Belady’s anomaly?
👉 LRU and Optimal

🔹 Programming Related

Q24. What input is required?
👉 Page reference string, number of frames.

Q25. What output is expected?
👉 Number of page faults and hits.

Q26. Which language is used?
👉 C / C++
